"Tanduay" originated from the word 'tanguay', an old Tagalog term for peninsula. It also means "low-lying land" such as in the case of an entire area in the city of Manila, including the San Miguel and Quiapo districts of the city. The area was once frequently flooded during the wet season leaving only a 'tanguay', which was encircled by the elevated water-levels of the estuaries of San Miguel and San Sebastian, and which Spanish cartographers referred to as "Isla de Tanduay".